    <article class="post-1894 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-love category-work tag-mogreet tag-responsive-web-design-2 tag-twitter-bootstrap tag-zurbs-foundation" id="post-1894">


<!-- Post Header
================================================== -->        
    <header class="center-all">
      <small class="preheader text-center">October 15, 2012</small>
      <hr class="sep-date"/>
    
      <h1 class="post-title">Mogreet</h1>
      <ul class="post-meta">
        <li><span class="post-meta-byline">Written by <a href="http://sosweetcreative.com/author/stephen-scaff" title="Posts by Stephen Scaff" rel="author">Stephen Scaff</a> and Posted in: <a href="http://sosweetcreative.com/category/love" title="View all posts in Love">Love</a> | <a href="http://sosweetcreative.com/category/work" title="View all posts in Work">Work</a></span></li>
      </ul>
    </header>

<!-- Post Content
================================================== -->        
    <div class="post-content">
      <figure><img src="http://sosweetcreative.com/wp-content/uploads/mogreet-home-800x500.jpg" alt="mogreet-home-800x500" class="aligncenter" /></figure>
<p>Our latest web project for Mogreet, Inc. is out the door! Built atop a customized framework combining Zurb&#8217;s Foundation and Twitter&#8217;s Bootstrap, this responsive gem is chalked full of CSS3 magic and a hefty dose of super awesomeness!</p>
<p>Mogreet is the leader in mobile marketing and video/rich media text messaging. They&#8217;ve developed a sniffy api for creating and monitoring mobile campaigns. Think MailChimp for MMS/SMS. Undoubtabley, you&#8217;ve seen those, &#8220;text this word to that number for this&#8230;&#8221; Well, that&#8217;s Mogreet.</p>
<p>On the dawn of launching their new platform and expanded service offerings, they knew that their old site had to go. They came to us with little beyond instructions to making it superbad. No problem.</p>
<figure><img src="http://sosweetcreative.com/wp-content/uploads/mogreet-home-full.jpg" alt="mogreet-home-full" class="aligncenter" /></figure>
<p>The purpose of the main site was to promote their new and existing services, while establishing a clear brand image for their online identity. This was accomplished via a tri-color palette, distinct and playful graphics, a strong focus on typography, and consistent UI features. We designed everything uder the root, main.mogreet.com, which includes their <a class="" title="Mogreet's Small Business Landing page by SoSweet! Creative" href="http://main.mogreet.com/smallbusiness.html">Small Business Landing page</a>, and created the graphics for their Developer portal.</p>
<figure><a href="http://sosweetcreative.com/wp-content/uploads/mogreet-whymogreet.jpg"><img src="http://sosweetcreative.com/wp-content/uploads/mogreet-whymogreet.jpg" alt="mogreet-whymogreet" class="aligncenter" /></a></figure>
<p>Mogreet did want us to build the site atop <a class="" title="Twitter Bootstrap" href="http://twitter.github.com/bootstrap/">Twitter&#8217;s Bootstrap</a> framework. But, these days, I&#8217;ve been working exclusively with <a class="" title="Zurb's Foundation" href="http://foundation.zurb.com/">Zurb&#8217;s Foundation</a> &#8211; at least in terms of its super clean, responsive grid. So, my solution was to combine the best features of both frameworks&#8230;sorta like Voltron. </p>
<figure><img src="http://sosweetcreative.com/wp-content/uploads/mogreet-mobiles.jpg" alt="mogreet-mobiles" class="aligncenter" /></figure>
<p>Essentially, I took Bootstrap&#8217;s mobile menu (and related scripts) , mixed it with Foundation&#8217;s percentage-based grid, sprinkled in some customizations, and expanded the badboy to 1140px&#8230;Viola! While not a fan of Bootstrap&#8217;s &#8220;span1&#8243; naming convention for columns, I did maintain it so the framework could be fairly plug and play for future pages/sites (replacing Foundation&#8217;s &#8220;one column&#8221; in class name only).  The end result is a streamlined framework for banging out responsive sites lickity split.</p>
<p>The design itself is illustration based and features a bunch of neato CCS3 schtuffs, like animations, transitions and transforms. And how about the planes soaring across the home&#8217;s hero section? Pretty sweet right? They were handled with those most magical keyframes (sorry IE), for a lightweight, pure CSS3 approach. With the <a title="Mogreet's Small Biz page" href="http://main.mogreet.com/smallbusiness.html">Small Business Landing Page</a>, I flipped the design script a bit, and used jquery backstretch to create a full screen, background image slideshow. A email sign up form sits pretty in a CSS3, imageless, 3d-ish, box.</p>
<figure><img src="http://sosweetcreative.com/wp-content/uploads/mogreet-smallbiz.jpg" alt="mogreet-smallbiz" class="aligncenter" /></figure>
<p>We&#8217;re fist pumping excited with the end product, and happy to report that the site is featured on all major CSS Awards, and a boatload of awesome design galleries. </p>
<hr/>
<h4>Check It Out!</h4>
<p><a class="" title="Mogreet's Site Live" href="http://main.mogreet.com">Mogreet.com</a>,<br />
<a class="" title="Mogreet web project in SoSweet! Creative's portfolio" href="/mogreet">In Our Portfolio</a></p>
